    description: "The triskele (or triskelion) is one of the oldest known symbols in human history, with examples carved into the entrance stone of Newgrange, the 5,200-year-old megalithic tomb in Ireland, predating the Egyptian pyramids by approximately 500 years. This triple spiral motif has been found across many ancient cultures, but it is most strongly associated with Celtic and pre-Celtic Irish tradition, where it remains a powerful symbol of Ireland's ancient spiritual heritage.\n\nThe three spirals of the triskele have been interpreted in numerous ways throughout history. In Celtic tradition, they represent the three realms: land, sea, and sky. In Druidic philosophy, they signify the three stages of life: youth, adulthood, and old age. Some interpretations connect them to the triple goddess (maiden, mother, crone) or to the Christian Trinity (which Celtic Christians readily adopted, seeing the triskele as proof that the Irish had always understood God's three-in-one nature).\n\nThe triskele's power as a symbol comes from its suggestion of perpetual motion. Unlike static symbols, the three spirals create a visual sense of movement and rotation, embodying the Celtic belief that life is not linear but cyclical - constantly turning, evolving, and returning. This dynamic quality makes the triskele a symbol not just of life's stages but of life's energy itself.\n\nIn modern Ireland, the triskele is experiencing a renaissance as a symbol of Irish identity, spirituality, and connection to the ancient past. It appears on jewelry, tattoos, pottery, and architecture. The triskele motif is used by organizations ranging from the Irish Air Corps to global Celtic heritage groups. As a lucky charm, it represents the belief that understanding and honoring life's cycles brings wisdom, balance, and good fortune.",
    meaning: "The triskele symbolizes the eternal cycle of life, the interconnection of past, present, and future, and the dynamic energy of constant growth and renewal. Its three spirals represent any number of trinities (land/sea/sky, mind/body/spirit, birth/life/death) united in perpetual motion. It embodies the Celtic belief that all things are connected and that life's energy never stops flowing.",
    howToUse: "Wear a triskele pendant for connection to Celtic spiritual energy and life's natural rhythms. Display triskele artwork in your home for balanced energy flow. The symbol is especially meaningful during times of transition, reminding the wearer that change is natural and cyclical. A triskele makes a thoughtful gift for milestones marking life's passages: births, weddings, and new beginnings.",
    funFact: "The Newgrange passage tomb in Ireland, where one of the most famous triskeles is carved, is aligned so that on the winter solstice (December 21), a shaft of sunlight illuminates the inner chamber for exactly 17 minutes. The triskele at the entrance has been greeting this annual light for over 5,000 years.",
